47 Four classes of case attracting the application of the language of unconscionability are described in Laws of Australia , Vol 35, Unfair Dealing, 35.5 Notion of Unconscionability [1]-[38]: 
 (i) Exploitation of vulnerability or weakness; 
 (ii) Abuse of position of trust or confidence; 




 (iii) Insistence upon rights in circumstances which make that harsh or oppressive; 




 (iv) Inequitable denial of legal obligations.

) 


24 Their Honours then discussed the meaning of the term "unconscionable" and stated:


 "42 The term "unconscionable" is used as a description of various grounds of equitable intervention to refuse enforcement of or to set aside transactions which offend equity and good conscience.
